<DOC><DOCNO> AP890224-0069 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0643EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Hirohito     02-24 0435</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Korea-Hirohito,0452</SECOND><HEAD>Korean Protesters Burn Japanese Flags To Denounce Hirohito</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Hirohito-Funeral, Bjt</HEAD><BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Protesters denouncing Emperor Hirohitoas ``mankind's biggest war criminal'' burned Japanese flags in twocities today and riot police blocked demonstrators from marching onthe Japanese Embassy.   Riot police with shields dispersed about 70 protesters who triedto march to the embassy after 200 people held an anti-Japanese rallyin a park and burned a flag to denounce Japanese war crimes. Policetook 10 marchers into custody.   ``Japan must apologize!'' and ``Let's drive out U.S. and Japaneseinfluence!'' protesters shouted.   In the southern city of Pusan, about 60 protesters burned aJapanese flag near the Japanese consulate and demanded Japanapologize for war atrocities, according to Yonhap, the South Koreannews agency.   Protesters in Seoul tried to march to the Japanese Embassy todemand an apology for Japan's harsh treatment of South Korea underthe colonial rule of Hirohito, whose funeral was held today in Tokyo.   Japan occupied Korea from 1910 to 1945.   ``Hirohito was mankind's biggest war criminal and our nationalfoe,'' said a statement by protesters. ``Japan has never made aformal apology to the Koreans for their wrongdoings.''   Moon Il-kwan, one of the backers of the nation's largestdissident alliance, was among those detained by police in Seoul.   Protesters in Seoul also shouted anti-American slogans anddenounced the scheduled visit Monday of President Bush. Radicalshave called for protests Saturday and Monday to protest the Bushtrip.   Police said a security alert was in effect from noon today untilmidnight Monday to block any protests against Bush. Riot policesquads were posted at intersections, government buildings and someembassies today in Seoul.   Radical students staged anti-government protests today at threeSeoul colleges to denounce the government and the United States.   In minor clashes, protesters at Sungshil and Sejong universitieshurled firebombs and rocks at riot police.   At Seoul National University, about 100 students held a peacefulanti-U.S. rally to demand Bush cancel his stop in Seoul and burned apaper effigy that students said represented the U.S. and SouthKorean governments.   Radical students and dissidents have said weekend protestes willalso be aimed at the government of South Korean President RohTae-woo, which celebrates its first anniversary Saturday.   Radicals claim the Roh government is a military dictatorshippropped up by the United States and demand the 42,000 U.S. troops inthe country under a mutual defense treaty be removed.   The radicals have little popular support, but authorities haveexpressed concern about their threat to hold violent protests.</TEXT></DOC>